

# Format:
#
# <type>[(<scope>)]: short description, imperative
# -----------------------------------------------< max width 50 chars
# <empty line>
# [<optional elaborate multiline description of your changes>]
# <empty line>
# [BREAKING CHANGE[: <how/what does it break?>]]
# <empty line>
# [<Closes #IssueNr, #IssueNr, ...>]
#
##########################
#
# Valid types are
#
#  - feat: commit is part of implementing a new feature or removing/changing an old one
#    - any change that alters the behaviour or structure of the public api is a
       BREAKING CHANGE
#  - fix: commit is part of a dedicated bug fix
#  - refactor: structural without behavioural changes
#    - no breaking changes!
#	 - no new features!
#  - build: changes to build system and/or external deps
#    - e.g.: upgrading pytorch version
#  - ci: changing continuous integration, e.g., github actions
#  - perf: improving performance, e.g., changing an O(n) to an O(log(n)) algorithm
#  - style: only changing whitespaces, formatting, no semantic changes to code
#  - docs: only changing documentation
#  - chore: changing other stuff not covered by the above types, e.g., changing `.gitignore`
#  - test: add missing or fix existing tests
#    - usually this will be system or integration tests as most unit tests
#      should evolve alongside the feature (TDD)
#
#
# Currently we have no fixed rules for scopes, pick one or several scopes (delimited by `,`)
# as you see fit. Often the name of the package where the code you're working on lives in
# is a good match
#
# Examples: vhdl, verilog, ir, torch, convolution, plugins, etc.
